Kirubia is among the nine stadiums promised by President Uhuru Kenyatta and his deputy Dr William Ruto during 2017 General Election campaigns.
In June this year, Sports, Heritage and Culture Cabinet Secretary, Amina Mohamed, toured the facility and promised the residents that the government was set to complete and launch the stadium in a month’s time, but to no avail.
After failing to meet the deadline, Tharaka-Nithi County Development Implementation and Coordination Committee led by County Commissioner; Ms Beverly Opwora, issued another deadline of September 30, which was also not achieved.





The contractor, Toddy Civil Engineering and Construction Company site manager, Boniface Shiveka, told Nation Sport Tuesday that the earliest the work could be completed was the end of February 2021.
“I am hoping that by the end of February 2021 the stadium will be ready for use,” said Mr Shiveka.
He said he had targeted to complete the work by the end of 2020 after missing several other deadlines, but there emerged some financial issues that delayed everything.
He said government also added him some work which was in the initial contract including demolition and construction of the perimeter wall which will take almost a whole month.



